Peroneus Longus Tendon Tears: Acute and Chronic
G. James Sammarco, M.D.

Peroneus Longus Tendon Tears: Acute and Chronic > ABSTRACT
Tear of the peroneus longus tendon can be difficult to diagnose and treat.
Fourteen cases of clinically proven tears are reported.
Patients ranged in age from 31 to 63 years.
There were 10 men and four women.
The onset of symptoms was acute in eight cases.
Chronic onset with slowly increasing pain occurred in six cases.
Despite acute onset of symptoms, only one patient was diagnosed within 2 weeks of his injury.
The others had symptom duration ranging from 7 to 48 months.

Peroneus Longus Tendon Tears: Acute and Chronic > ABSTRACT
Twelve tears were located distally as the tendon turned into the cuboid groove.
An 0s peroneum visible on x-ray was present in six cases, absent in seven cases, and cartilaginous in one case.
The 0s peroneum was involved in the tear in three cases.
Excision of part or all of the 0s peroneum was performed in four cases with a bridging tendon graft required in one case.
A plantaris tendon graft was required in one case in which an 0s peroneum was absent.

Peroneus Longus Tendon Tears: Acute and Chronic > ABSTRACT
Patients with acute onset of symptoms tended to fare better than those with chronic onset of symptoms, regardless of the length of time from onset to time of surgery.
Associated pathology in the peroneus brevis tendon was common, occurring in nine cases.
These patients seemed to have a better surgical outcome than those with only a tear of the peroneus longus tendon.

Associated findings affected diagnosis by masking symptoms but did not alter the outcome of treatment.

The presence or absence of an 0s peroneum did not affect symptoms or treatment, but its presence on x-rays may aid in the diagnosis if migration of part or all of the sesamoid occurs.

Peroneus Longus Tendon Tears: Acute and Chronic > INTRODUCTION
Injuries to the peroneus longus have been considered uncommon.
The true incidence and significance of a tear in this tendon is still elusive.
The tear may be acute or chronic.
Injury may occur alone or in association with a peroneus brevis tendon tear, and ankle function can be severely compromised by complete disruption of the tendon6 (D. Baxter, personal communication, 1994).

Peroneus Longus Tendon Tears: Acute and Chronic > INTRODUCTION
Acute injuries of the peroneus longus tendon include tendinitis, avulsion of the tendon at or through the 0s peroneum, lacerations, and dislocation at the lateral malleolus of the ankle with or without a “rim fracture” of the fibula.

Peroneus Longus Tendon Tears: Acute and Chronic > INTRODUCTION
Chronic tears are more subtle in onset and develop without an initiating injury.
They include rents in the tendon either alone or in association with another localized disease, such as ankle or subtalar arthritis and ankle i n~ tab i

i t y.~~, ’~ A chronic tear is longitudinal in orientation and commonly occurs at the cuboid.
If an 0s peroneum is present, it may fragment as the tendon gradually tears and retracts.
Treatment of the injury depends on the type of lesion, its chronicity, and the age and activity level of the patient.
The purpose of this report is to present the author’s experience with 14 cases of peroneus longus tear.
A description of the etiology, symptoms, demographics, associated findings with the peroneus brevis tendon, treatment, and outcome are presented.
Patients with an acute peroneus longus tear had a history of an initiating significant event, acute lateral foot pain, occasional development of varus deformity, lateral foot swelling, and tenderness at the anterior, inferior, and lateral calcaneal border.
Patients with a chronic peroneus longus tear had no initiating event and had symptoms that developed insidiously and appeared to be related to overuse.

All clin- ical notes and x-rays were personally reviewed by the author.
The patients selected for this study were those with a clinical diagnosis of peroneus longus tendon tear.
Age, sex, and side of lesion were recorded.
All patients were Caucasian.
Acute or chronic in onset of symptoms was recorded.
Occupation and activity causing symptoms were evaluated.
Time from onset of symptoms to diagnosis and its initial treatment was studied.
Diagnostic tests, including x-rays and mag- netic resonance imaging (MRI) were reviewed.
Follow- ing initial diagnosis, nonsurgical treatment included immobilization for a period of at least 2 weeks.
Non- steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs were prescribed at initial diagnosis, followed by a rehabilitation program stressing flexibility.
At operation, the size and location of the tear and associated findings were noted.
The patient did not return to preinjury activity until an ex- ercise program had been performed.
This included conditioning and stretching exercises.
An ankle brace (Aircast) to help control inversion was used until symp- toms subsided.
A lace-up ankle brace was prescribed when the patient returned to sports.
At operation, the size and location of the tear and associated findings were noted.

The average age of patients was 46.5 years.
The average age of patients with acute onset of symptoms was 39.5 years and of patients with chronic onset of symptoms 55.8 years.
The average age of men was injury.
The definition of acute onset (symptoms occurring within a very short period of time prior to the diagnosis) was found to be inappropriate.
Patients were classified as having a chronic tear if they had an insidious onset of symptoms over a prolonged period of time without an acute traumatic episode.
This created a clear difference between the two groups.
A patient had an excellent outcome if there was no pain or deformity, a full range of ankle motion, and unrestricted activity.
A good outcome was noted if the patient had minimal or no pain, minimal deformity, a full range of motion, and unrestricted activity on returning to preinjury status.
A fair outcome consisted of moderate pain with or without mild deformity and loss of motion.
Activity was limited by endurance or choice and the patient did not return to preinjury status.

The average time between onset of symptoms and surgery in acute cases was 14.9 months (range 7-48 months).

Three of the 14 patients had associated ankle ligament instability (two acute and one chronic).

The surgical treatment of the eight patients with acute peroneus longus tears was direct repair in four cases, i.e., suturing the longitudinal tear of the tendon (Fig. 1).
Two additional patients required debridement of the tendon in addition to the repair.
One more patient had excision of a fragmented 0s peroneum with repair augmented by a fascia1 graft (Fig. 2).
The final patient with a complete rupture of the tendon beneath the cuboid underwent tenodesis of the tendon to the cuboid.
This was reinforced with a plantaris tendon graft (Fig. 3).
Six patients with an acute peroneus longus tear and an associated peroneus brevis tear had the brevis tear treated by suture of the tendon tear (N = 4), debridement with tendon graft using an adjacent anomalous peroneocalcaneal muscle tendon to reinforce the repair (N = l), and tendon tenodesis of neum and associated fragments with tendon repair in two cases.

Three cases with acute onset of symptoms and three cases with chronic onset of symptoms had a visible 0s peroneum on x-ray.
If the 0s peroneum was fractured in the acute group and a portion remained with the proximal tendon, the proximal fragments migrated to the lateral tuberosity of the calcaneus.
This was visible on serial x-rays over a period of weeks (Fig. 2).
Only two patients with acute onset of symptoms had positive x-ray findings, one with soft tissue mass and the other with fragmentation of the 0s peroneum.
Three patients with chronic symptoms had positive x-ray findings.
One patient exhibited migration of the 0s peroneum proximally on serial x-rays.
One patient had clinical varus of the hindfoot on weightbearing x-rays, and one patient had fragmentation of the 0s peroneum.
MRI was performed on six patients with an acute onset of symptoms.
It showed an associated tear of the peroneus brevis tendon in five patients (Fig. 4).
This was confirmed in all five cases at surgery.
MRI was performed on four patients with chronic onset of symptoms (Fig. 5).
It revealed a tear of the longus in all cases and one associated tear of the peroneus brevis tendon.
In four patients, no MRI was performed.
MRI was important in confirming the diagnosis of peroneus longus tear in patients who did not have an 0s peroneum and in patients who had a fragmented 0s peroneum but for whom the diagnosis was in doubt (Fig. 4).
Diagnosis was confirmed on nine of the 10 patients.
One patient with an acute onset of symptoms had no evidence of a tear on MRI, but a tendon tear was present at surgery.

A walker boot (Bledsoe) with limited motion was used and a range of motion and strengthening program was then begun.
After 6 weeks, the patient was placed in an ankle brace.
The period of time for return to work was often several months following surgery.

One patient (case 14) died of an unrelated cause 2 months after surgery.
Of the patients who had acute onset of symptoms, two rated their results as excellent, five rated them as good, and one rated the result as fair.
Of the patients who had chronic onset of symptoms, one rated the outcome as excellent, two rated it as good, one rated it as fair, and one rated the outcome as poor.
Return to work occurred between 4 months and 9 months after surgery (average 5.2 months).
Five patients did not return to employment due to retirement, student status, or death.

Tear of the peroneus longus tendon is not rare.
Symptoms may be acute or chronic in onset.
The tear occurs alone, but it may also occur in association with a tear of the peroneus brevis tendon.
It may be a single tear or multiple tears within the tendon.
It may also be longitudinal, transverse partial, or complete and may be associated with a fracture of the 0s peroneum.

Successful nonoperative treatment The length of the peroneus longus tendon tear varied but had no influence on the outcome in either acute or chronic tears.
The presence or absence of an 0s peroneum also did not seem to affect the outcome of surgery.
If an 0s peroneum was present and fractured, part or all was excised and a repair with or without tendon graft was performed.
If a complete tranverse rupture was present, a tenodesis was performed to the cuboid (case 4).
If a simple tear was present, a repair was performed after debridement of the lesion.

I > I
Two cases in the chronic group had peroneus brevis tendon rupture and contracture, requiring tenodesis to the calcaneus (cases 2 and 11).
One of these required a tendon graft.
There was one good outcome and one excellent outcome.
The other peroneus brevis tears were repaired directly.

I > I
When complete disruption of the tendon is present and the tendon cannot be fully advanced at surgery, reattachment of the tendon to the distal stump can be bridged by use of a tendon graft such as the plantaris tendon.16 In none of the cases reported here was the peroneus longus tendon completely torn with the muscle retracted and fixed.

I > I > CONCLUSION
Tears of the peroneus longus tendon fall into two categories.
Acute tears have a single event that initiates symptoms.
Chronic tears have no initiating event.
Tears tend to occur in adults and are charac- teristically longitudinal but may also be complete and transverse.
Men are more commonly affected than women.
Symptoms include lateral heel pain, swelling, and tenderness near the cuboid with an antalgic gait and varus foot positioning.
MRI is an effective diagnostic tool in confirming the diagnosis.

Treatment of the peroneus longus tear varies.
Those patients with pain and demonstrable loss of function are candidates for surgical reconstruction.
Tear of the peroneus brevis tendon and lateral ankle ligament laxity are common associated findings.
The absence of an 0s peroneum may be misleading and cause delay in diagnosis.
Those with acute onset of symptoms tend to fare better than those without an initiating event precipitating symptoms.
However, surgical repair of all pathologic conditions often results in good or excellent outcomes whether the tear is acute or chronic.
